After studying backend systems, I realized most errors shouldn’t be exceptions at all.

5 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Centre for Ageing Better on UnsplashFor a long time, I thought good error handling meant adding more try-catch blocks. Something might fail? Wrap it. Calling a database? Wrap it. Reading a file? Wrap it. Talking to another service? Wrap it.
Back then, I believed I was writing “safe code.”
I wasn’t.
I was writing code that hid problems.
One day, while debugging an issue in a backend service, I spent almost two hours trying to understand why users were receiving empty responses. The application wasn’t crashing. No alarms were firing. Everything looked healthy.
Eventually, I found the culprit. Someone — including a younger version of myself — had written:
try {
processPayment();
} catch (Exception e) {
return null;
}
• No logs.

• No alerts.

• No visibility.
The exception disappeared into a black hole. That’s when I started studying how production systems handle failures. After reading engineering blogs from companies like Netflix, Uber, and Stripe, and after spending countless hours debugging real…
